@{i}Why a duck?@{ui} FidoNet node: (1:163/109.4).


@EndNode

@Node "Cursor movement" "icebbs_demo.guide/Cursor movement"
@Next "Erasing"
@Prev "Amiga ANSI"
@Toc "Amiga ANSI"

Cursor Positioning or Movement
------------------------------

   To move the cursor to a specified position: @{b}ESC [#;#h@{ub} where the
first @{b}#@{ub} is the desired line number and the second the desired column.
To move the cursor up without changing columns: @{b}ESC [#a@{ub} where @{b}#@{ub}
specifies the number of lines moved. To move the cursor to a specified
horizontal and vertical position: @{b}ESC [#;#f@{ub} where @{b}#@{ub} means first the
line number and the second @{b}#@{ub} the column number. To get a cursor
position report: @{b}ESC [#;#r@{ub} where the first @{b}#@{ub} specifies the current line
and the second @{b}#@{ub} specifies the current column. To move the cursor down:
@{b}ESC [#b@{ub} where @{b}#@{ub} specifies the number of lines moved down. To move the
cursor forward: @{b}ESC [#C@{ub} where @{b}#@{ub} specifies the number of columns moved.
To move the cursor backward: @{b}ESC [#d@{ub} where @{b}#@{ub} specifies the number of
columns moved.  To save the cursor position: @{b}ESC [s@{ub} and to restore it:
@{b}ESC [u@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Erasing" "icebbs_demo.guide/Erasing"
@Next "Colour graphics"
@Prev "Cursor movement"
@Toc "Amiga ANSI"

Erasing the Screen and Erasing a Line
-------------------------------------

   To do a CLS (erase screen move cursor to home position): @{b}ESC [2j@{ub} To
erase from cursor to end of line: @{b}ESC [k@{ub}


@EndNode

@Node "Colour graphics" "icebbs_demo.guide/Colour graphics"
@Next "Text attributes"
@Prev "Erasing"
@Toc "Amiga ANSI"

ANSI Colour Graphics
--------------------

   To set the colour/graphics attributes, enter @{b}ESC [#;#m@{ub} where the
first @{b}#@{ub} is the desired foreground colour and the second is the desired
background colour.  Select colours from the list below: (Note: the
following Amiga colours were with preferences settings of blue, black,
orange and white-the default AmigaDOS 1.3 colours).

   In the following tables the Amiga ANSI result is in italics (it is
the second result).

@{b}30@{ub}
     black foreground

     @{i}blue foreground (text)@{ui}

@{b}31@{ub}
     red foreground

     @{i}white foreground (text)@{ui}

@{b}32@{ub}
     green foreground

     @{i}black foreground (text)@{ui}

@{b}33@{ub}
     yellow foreground

     @{i}orange foreground (text)@{ui}

@{b}34@{ub}
     blue foreground

     @{i}blue foreground (text)@{ui}

@{b}35@{ub}
     magenta foreground

     @{i}white foreground (text)@{ui}

@{b}36@{ub}
     cyan foreground

     @{i}black foreground (text)@{ui}

@{b}37@{ub}
     white foreground

     @{i}orange foreground (text)@{ui}

@{b}38@{ub}
     unknown

     @{i}unknown@{ui}

@{b}39@{ub}
     unknown

     @{i}unknown@{ui}

@{b}40@{ub}
     black background

     @{i}blue background@{ui}

@{b}41@{ub}
     red background

     @{i}white Background@{ui}

@{b}42@{ub}
     green background

     @{i}black background@{ui}

@{b}43@{ub}
     yellow background

     @{i}orange background@{ui}

@{b}44@{ub}
     blue background

     @{i}blue background@{ui}

@{b}45@{ub}
     magenta background

     @{i}white background@{ui}

@{b}46@{ub}
     cyan background

     @{i}black Background@{ui}

@{b}47@{ub}
     white background

     @{i}orange background@{ui}

@{b}48@{ub}
     unknown

     @{i}unknown@{ui}

@{b}49@{ub}
     unknown

     @{i}unknown@{ui}

   NOTE: Please note that for both the foreground and background
sections, the colours repeat after each four codes; ie: blue text = 30
or 34; blue background= 40 or 44. (unless you use a WorkBench or screen
with more than 4 colours) Also, as long as you know the escape code for
the foreground colour, the same colour for background will be 10
numbers higher.


@EndNode

@Node "Text attributes" "icebbs_demo.guide/Text attributes"
@Prev "Colour graphics"
@Toc "Amiga ANSI"

Additional ANSI Attributes
--------------------------

   To set additional attributes enter: @{b}ESC [#m@{ub} where @{b}#@{ub} is the number of
the desired attribute.  Select attributes from the list below: 0  all
attributes off (defaults to original Preferences settings)

@{b}0@{ub}
     all ANSI attributes off

     @{i}all ANSI attributes off@{ui}

@{b}1@{ub}
     bold on

     @{i}bold on@{ui}

@{b}2@{ub}
     unknown

     @{i}turns text black@{ui}

@{b}3@{ub}
     Italics on

     @{i}italics on@{ui}

@{b}4@{ub}
     underscore

     @{i}underscore@{ui}

@{b}5@{ub}
     blink

     @{i}does not work on amiga@{ui}

@{b}6@{ub}
     unknown

     @{i}unknown@{ui}

@{b}7@{ub}
     reverse video

     @{i}reverse video@{ui}

@{b}8@{ub}
     invisible

     @{i}invisible@{ui}


@EndNode

